285
00:19:47,554 --> 00:19:51,556
Dang it. Dang it!

286
00:19:54,694 --> 00:19:56,327
Spec-5 farley?

287
00:19:56,329 --> 00:19:57,862
Yes, sir!

288
00:19:57,864 --> 00:19:59,363
So what's the mission, sir?

289
00:19:59,365 --> 00:20:00,631
Unless you can't tell me,

290
00:20:00,633 --> 00:20:02,333
like if we're operatin'
on a need-to-know basis.

291
00:20:02,335 --> 00:20:03,734
We are, and you don't.

292
00:20:03,736 --> 00:20:06,370
Yes, sir.

293
00:20:06,372 --> 00:20:08,606
Where you from, farley?

294
00:20:08,608 --> 00:20:10,641
Iowa, sir. Or as my Uncle
Fergus liked to put it,

295
00:20:10,643 --> 00:20:14,312
I owe a hell of a lot of
money on them farm loans.

296
00:20:14,314 --> 00:20:16,781
He doesn't say much about it
since the thresher accident.

297
00:20:16,783 --> 00:20:18,800
Mama likes to say you can
hardly tell anything happened

298
00:20:18,801 --> 00:20:20,818
unless you get up real
close, but I beg to differ.

299
00:20:20,820 --> 00:20:22,420
You been on a farm?

300
00:20:22,422 --> 00:20:23,621
Yes, sir. My daddy
owns a dairy farm,

301
00:20:23,623 --> 00:20:25,823
seein' as I bein'
from the corn state.

302
00:20:25,825 --> 00:20:27,325
So you've had
experience with animals.

303
00:20:27,327 --> 00:20:28,659
Yes, sir.

304
00:20:28,661 --> 00:20:30,328
Just none of 'em good.

305
00:20:30,330 --> 00:20:31,395
I don't know what it is.

306
00:20:31,397 --> 00:20:32,763
Animals just
don't seem to like me.

307
00:20:32,765 --> 00:20:34,632
Never have,
probably never will.

308
00:20:34,634 --> 00:20:35,700
And that didn't make life
easier growin' up on a farm.

309
00:20:35,702 --> 00:20:37,401
Tell you that.

310
00:20:37,403 --> 00:20:38,586
Shoot, one of the main reasons

311
00:20:38,587 --> 00:20:39,770
why I joined the army
in the first place.

312
00:20:39,772 --> 00:20:42,506
Get away from
all the dang animals.

313
00:20:48,548 --> 00:20:53,517
Gilman, hey, I need
25 submariners at 300 per. Ok?

314
00:20:56,422 --> 00:20:58,823
Gilman, may I remind you
I have friends

315
00:20:58,825 --> 00:21:00,825
with absolutely no regard for
the sanctity of human life, ok?

316
00:21:00,827 --> 00:21:04,395
I say the word, I have your head in
a bag on my desk tomorrow morning.

317
00:21:04,397 --> 00:21:07,565
Hang on. General. It's done.

318
00:21:07,567 --> 00:21:10,534
425 per.

319
00:21:10,536 --> 00:21:12,470
Pleasure doing business
with you, sir.

320
00:21:12,472 --> 00:21:14,472
Yes, sir, and give my regards

321
00:21:14,474 --> 00:21:15,806
to your lovely wife
and daughter.

322
00:21:15,808 --> 00:21:19,543
I didn't mean
anything by that, sir.

323
00:21:19,545 --> 00:21:20,878
I gotta go. I got a call
on the other line.

324
00:21:20,880 --> 00:21:22,280
All right, thank you.

325
00:21:22,282 --> 00:21:23,547
Gilman, so where were we?

326
00:21:23,549 --> 00:21:25,650
I think
I had your head in a bag,

327
00:21:25,652 --> 00:21:28,552
350? Done.

328
00:21:28,554 --> 00:21:31,656
All right. Send them to general
John Richardson in danang, please.

329
00:21:31,658 --> 00:21:33,291
Thanks, pal.

330
00:21:33,293 --> 00:21:34,525
And, oh, by the way, gilman?

331
00:21:34,527 --> 00:21:36,661
I'd still let somebody
taste your food.

332
00:21:44,837 --> 00:21:47,538
I thought you were dead.

333
00:21:47,540 --> 00:21:49,307
You mean you hoped I was dead.

334
00:21:49,309 --> 00:21:52,376
What can I do for you guys?

335
00:21:52,378 --> 00:21:53,778
You're a requisitions officer.

336
00:21:53,780 --> 00:21:58,449
Well, we require something.

337
00:22:03,890 --> 00:22:05,356
Not even funny.

338
00:22:05,358 --> 00:22:07,458
We need an elephant
by tomorrow.

339
00:22:07,460 --> 00:22:09,460
Or you don't you think
you could do it?

340
00:22:09,462 --> 00:22:11,762
Please.

341
00:22:11,764 --> 00:22:13,564
Spare me
the I-dare-you crap, Cahill.

342
00:22:13,566 --> 00:22:17,535
Everybody knows I can get
anything anywhere anytime.

343
00:22:17,537 --> 00:22:20,371
Just so happens I'm
startin' 5 days of r-and-r.

344
00:22:20,373 --> 00:22:24,542
This time tomorrow I'll be sittin'
on a beach in Hawaii, my friend.

345
00:22:24,544 --> 00:22:26,577
You're getting us the elephant.

346
00:22:26,579 --> 00:22:28,980
Or what?

347
00:22:28,981 --> 00:22:31,382
You gonna still try to hold that
business with the 64th over my head?

348
00:22:31,384 --> 00:22:33,651
Come on. So the pork
was a little off.

349
00:22:33,653 --> 00:22:35,453
A little off?

350
00:22:35,455 --> 00:22:38,489
I know men who spent a week on the
latrine because of that pork.

351
00:22:38,491 --> 00:22:40,624
It's old news, Cahill.

352
00:22:40,626 --> 00:22:41,892
I got too many friends
in high places

353
00:22:41,894 --> 00:22:43,761
to go down for something
small-time like that now.

354
00:22:43,763 --> 00:22:47,565
Oh, I know other things
about you, poole.

355
00:22:47,567 --> 00:22:49,667
Let me tell you
something, Cahill.

356
00:22:49,669 --> 00:22:51,435
There isn't anything you know

357
00:22:51,437 --> 00:22:54,805
that's gonna keep me from gettin'
on that plane to Honolulu.

358
00:23:04,751 --> 00:23:07,585
Doyle: 180 Miles
in the middle of a war.

359
00:23:07,587 --> 00:23:09,387
We can get a truck and drive
it up close to dak nhe.

360
00:23:09,389 --> 00:23:11,455
That'll take about 3 days.

361
00:23:11,457 --> 00:23:12,690
And another day to walk it in.

362
00:23:12,692 --> 00:23:14,592
We'll get there by Friday.

363
00:23:14,594 --> 00:23:16,927
Actually, I was thinking more
along the lines of air travel.

364
00:23:16,929 --> 00:23:18,696
I lined up a cargo plane

365
00:23:18,698 --> 00:23:20,765
to meet us at an airstrip
near ban don, ok?

366
00:23:20,767 --> 00:23:23,100
We fly the elephant down
to this old CIA airstrip

367
00:23:23,102 --> 00:23:24,902
about a 3-hour walk
from dak nhe,

368
00:23:24,904 --> 00:23:26,771
then your montagnard friends
have their elephant

369
00:23:26,773 --> 00:23:28,773
by 2:00 this afternoon, I'm
sitting on the beach in waikiki

370
00:23:28,775 --> 00:23:30,174
in time to see the sunset.

371
00:23:30,176 --> 00:23:34,412
And you wanted a week!
Good job, poole!

372
00:23:34,414 --> 00:23:36,547
We're coming up on ban don now.

373
00:23:36,549 --> 00:23:39,483
There's no place to land
in the rice paddies.

374
00:23:39,485 --> 00:23:42,453
We'll have to go to an I.Z.
Behind the village.

375
00:23:42,455 --> 00:23:43,854
It was real hot here
2 weeks ago.

376
00:23:43,856 --> 00:23:46,424
Probably ok now.

377
00:23:46,426 --> 00:23:48,426
Probably? We're gonna
land on a "probably"?

378
00:23:48,428 --> 00:23:49,660
Lock and load!

379
00:24:11,150 --> 00:24:13,150
Hey, this isn't that bad.

380
00:24:13,152 --> 00:24:15,686
It's kind of peaceful, really.

381
00:24:15,688 --> 00:24:18,556
All right, move out.

382
00:24:26,599 --> 00:24:29,500
Well, Cahill,
you want elephants,

383
00:24:29,502 --> 00:24:31,602
I give you elephants.

384
00:24:31,604 --> 00:24:34,505
Beautiful elephants, I might
add, at no extra cost.

385
00:24:34,507 --> 00:24:35,840
Knowing you, poole,

386
00:24:35,842 --> 00:24:38,843
they're probably big
puppets with men inside.

387
00:24:38,845 --> 00:24:41,479
Let's go.

388
00:24:56,596 --> 00:24:58,162
Y b'ham?

389
00:25:01,601 --> 00:25:03,701
Let me handle the negotiation.

390
00:25:03,703 --> 00:25:05,803
I already talked to
this guy on the radio.

391
00:25:05,805 --> 00:25:09,840
Thinks he's tough, but I'm
gonna crack him like a walnut.

392
00:25:35,268 --> 00:25:37,167
Oh, you're killing me.

393
00:25:37,169 --> 00:25:38,836
What's the problem?

394
00:25:38,838 --> 00:25:40,271
I thought you could
negotiate anything.

395
00:25:40,273 --> 00:25:41,939
I can with leverage. Problem
is we don't have any.

396
00:25:41,941 --> 00:25:43,707
He doesn't care if he sells
the elephant or not.

397
00:25:43,709 --> 00:25:45,276
We don't make his price,
he blows the deal.

398
00:25:45,278 --> 00:25:47,245
What's his price?

399
00:25:47,246 --> 00:25:49,213
Problem number 2.
He wants 60,000 piasters.

400
00:25:49,215 --> 00:25:50,214
The requisition form
captain Doyle gave me

401
00:25:50,216 --> 00:25:51,248
is only good for 50, so...

402
00:25:51,250 --> 00:25:53,784
that's it?
Hell, 10,000 piasters...

403
00:25:53,786 --> 00:25:54,852
that's only about 150 bucks.

404
00:25:54,854 --> 00:25:56,787
We can raise that between us.

405
00:25:56,789 --> 00:25:59,256
No. You tell him 50,000
is our final offer.

406
00:25:59,258 --> 00:26:00,941
We can do it.

407
00:26:00,942 --> 00:26:02,625
Private funds can't be used
for an official purchase

408
00:26:02,628 --> 00:26:04,728
as per regulations.
It's also an order.

409
00:26:04,730 --> 00:26:07,231
Understood? Tell him.

410
00:26:08,834 --> 00:26:13,304
I get it. It's a perfect
way out for you.

411
00:26:13,306 --> 00:26:14,939
You blow the deal,
and the mission is over.

412
00:26:14,941 --> 00:26:18,609
It's what you wanted
from the beginning.

413
00:26:18,611 --> 00:26:21,779
We're going back to the I.Z.
And call for a ride.

414
00:26:21,781 --> 00:26:23,847
Let's go.

415
00:26:24,817 --> 00:26:26,183
Poole, let's move it.

416
00:26:26,185 --> 00:26:28,285
Ok, 50,000.

417
00:26:33,960 --> 00:26:36,727
You're quite
a negotiator, Doyle.

418
00:26:39,265 --> 00:26:43,334
Gracious sir, perhaps now
we could go to the river

419
00:26:43,336 --> 00:26:44,735
and pick our elephant.

420
00:26:44,737 --> 00:26:47,705
River? 50,000 don't
get elephant in river.

421
00:26:47,707 --> 00:26:50,307
50,000 get you Bo-tat.

422
00:26:50,309 --> 00:26:53,210
Bo-tat!

423
00:26:56,315 --> 00:26:57,314
Uh-oh.

424
00:27:01,187 --> 00:27:03,253
Beat it.

425
00:27:11,897 --> 00:27:15,265
Bo-tat is she, not he.

426
00:27:15,267 --> 00:27:17,935
Boy is linh.
Boy go with Bo-tat.

427
00:27:17,937 --> 00:27:21,338
What? No, boy no go
with Bo-tat.

428
00:27:21,340 --> 00:27:23,741
Boy go with Bo-tat.

429
00:27:23,743 --> 00:27:25,275
We're going to a village
far away.

430
00:27:25,277 --> 00:27:26,644
I'm sure linh's family...

431
00:27:26,646 --> 00:27:29,647
boy has no family. All killed.

432
00:27:29,649 --> 00:27:30,881
In the war?

433
00:27:30,883 --> 00:27:33,283
No. Hit by falling star.

434
00:27:35,187 --> 00:27:36,920
Yes, in war.

435
00:27:36,922 --> 00:27:38,922
Which side?

436
00:27:38,924 --> 00:27:40,391
It matter?

437
00:27:40,393 --> 00:27:43,227
I think it's better
if the boy stays here.

438
00:27:43,229 --> 00:27:47,331
He not belong here.
From north, not our people.

439
00:27:47,333 --> 00:27:49,900
We might as well
take him with us.

440
00:27:49,902 --> 00:27:52,236
N-no. We are not
taking a kid with us.

441
00:27:52,238 --> 00:27:53,871
He'll be my responsibility.

442
00:27:53,873 --> 00:27:55,239
No, captain. All right.

443
00:27:57,710 --> 00:27:59,877
Anyone else here know
how to work an elephant?

444
00:27:59,879 --> 00:28:01,445
I was in love with
a fat woman once,

445
00:28:01,447 --> 00:28:02,946
but she never listened to me.

446
00:28:02,948 --> 00:28:06,984
Oh. Mr. Y b'ham,
you must know how

447
00:28:06,986 --> 00:28:08,452
to work an elephant,
right, sir?

448
00:28:08,454 --> 00:28:10,854
I live with elephants
all my life.

449
00:28:10,856 --> 00:28:12,423
I learn nothing?

450
00:28:12,425 --> 00:28:16,860
Is this guy sarcastic,
or is it just me?

451
00:28:25,337 --> 00:28:27,705
Great. Would you like
to come with us, sir?

452
00:28:27,707 --> 00:28:29,740
20,000 piasters.

453
00:28:29,742 --> 00:28:31,241
Deal.

454
00:28:31,243 --> 00:28:33,494
Good job, Doyle.

455
00:28:33,495 --> 00:28:35,746
I think Mr. Y b'ham
would be a wonderful choice.

456
00:28:35,748 --> 00:28:37,214
Just one problem.

457
00:28:37,216 --> 00:28:38,882
What?

458
00:28:38,884 --> 00:28:41,418
He doesn't stare into space
because he's a wise old soul.

459
00:28:41,420 --> 00:28:43,253
He does it because
he's blind as a bat.

460
00:28:43,255 --> 00:28:46,256
Y b'ham not blind.
Y b'ham can...

461
00:28:46,258 --> 00:28:49,359
y b'ham is blind.

462
00:28:51,430 --> 00:28:53,230
10,000 piasters?

463
00:29:09,215 --> 00:29:10,347
Farley: It's a nice view.

464
00:29:10,349 --> 00:29:11,415
Ashford: What nice view?

465
00:29:11,417 --> 00:29:14,918
All I can see
is an elephant's butt.

466
00:29:24,463 --> 00:29:26,230
<i>Parlez-vous francais?</i>

467
00:29:27,767 --> 00:29:29,466
Any luck?

468
00:29:29,468 --> 00:29:32,369
I tried vietnamese,
Cambodian, French,

469
00:29:32,371 --> 00:29:34,271
and 3 dialects of jeh.

470
00:29:37,910 --> 00:29:39,343
Keep an eye on him.

471
00:29:39,345 --> 00:29:41,979
He's on an elephant.
He's hard to miss.

472
00:29:41,981 --> 00:29:44,281
You know what I mean.

473
00:29:44,283 --> 00:29:46,350
We don't know which side
killed his family.

474
00:29:46,352 --> 00:29:48,452
It could've been us.
He might hate Americans.

475
00:29:48,454 --> 00:29:49,987
We don't know, and until we do,

476
00:29:49,989 --> 00:29:51,321
he can't be trusted. Doyle...

477
00:29:51,323 --> 00:29:54,291
he right. Linh
can't be trusted.

478
00:29:56,228 --> 00:29:59,997
Linh no trust Americans.
Americans not trust linh.

479
00:29:59,999 --> 00:30:03,367
Everything's number one, a-ok.

480
00:30:25,324 --> 00:30:27,524
That elephant just came along
to say good-bye, right?

481
00:30:27,526 --> 00:30:29,893
You're not actually thinking
of putting that on my plane?

482
00:30:29,895 --> 00:30:30,894
What's the problem?

483
00:30:30,896 --> 00:30:33,430
What's the problem?

484
00:30:33,432 --> 00:30:34,464
It's an elephant.

485
00:30:34,466 --> 00:30:35,966
Yeah, but, major...

486
00:30:35,968 --> 00:30:37,568
no, no, no. You see,
you cannot put an elephant

487
00:30:37,570 --> 00:30:39,336
on an airplane.

488
00:30:39,338 --> 00:30:41,305
Suppose it starts to panic
and starts moving around?

489
00:30:41,307 --> 00:30:43,473
I lose trim,
the plane goes down.

490
00:30:43,475 --> 00:30:45,008
We all buy the farm.

491
00:30:45,010 --> 00:30:46,577
That's important,
what he just said.

492
00:30:46,579 --> 00:30:48,245
No, no, no.

493
00:30:48,247 --> 00:30:49,847
It's not getting
aboard the plane

494
00:30:49,849 --> 00:30:51,281
unless it's dead.

495
00:30:51,283 --> 00:30:54,451
Now, I'd be happy to oblige...

496
00:30:54,453 --> 00:30:56,486
If you've all grown
too attached to it.

497
00:30:56,488 --> 00:30:57,588
No!

498
00:30:57,590 --> 00:30:59,590
Linh, it's ok.

499
00:30:59,592 --> 00:31:02,226
No one's gonna shoot Bo-tat.

500
00:31:04,463 --> 00:31:05,996
Doyle.

501
00:31:10,436 --> 00:31:12,870
Poole.

502
00:31:12,872 --> 00:31:14,371
Do you have a package

503
00:31:14,373 --> 00:31:16,373
for a Dr. David poole,
d.V.M., on board?

504
00:31:16,375 --> 00:31:17,941
Yeah, I do.

505
00:31:24,550 --> 00:31:27,918
Here we go, gentlemen.
Animal tranquilizer.

506
00:31:27,920 --> 00:31:30,387
She won't move an inch.

507
00:31:30,389 --> 00:31:32,289
Bo-tat's gonna take
a big nap-nap.

508
00:31:32,291 --> 00:31:34,258
Hey, nice try,
but I don't care.

509
00:31:34,260 --> 00:31:36,593
See, my orders say nothing
about lifting an elephant.

510
00:31:36,595 --> 00:31:40,297
Gentlemen, you have a good war.

511
00:31:40,299 --> 00:31:45,002
Ahem, major, maybe
you should read this.

512
00:31:46,572 --> 00:31:49,239
Ok?

513
00:31:49,241 --> 00:31:50,474
This operation's top-secret,

514
00:31:50,476 --> 00:31:51,575
and that's why
you never heard anything

515
00:31:51,577 --> 00:31:53,010
about our large mammal
friend over there.

516
00:31:53,012 --> 00:31:54,544
As a matter of fact,
if anybody asks,

517
00:31:54,546 --> 00:31:57,014
you're moving
a shipment of tuna.

518
00:31:57,016 --> 00:31:58,448
Tuna?

519
00:31:58,450 --> 00:32:00,284
Tuna.

520
00:32:02,021 --> 00:32:03,687
Moving an elephant.

521
